92
00:07:29,097 --> 00:07:34,085
Breaking a cryptographic system
involves finding the plain text without

93
00:07:34,085 --> 00:07:35,540
the decryption key.

94
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:42,070
The attack models of a cyber system
depend on the amount of information

95
00:07:42,070 --> 00:07:43,860
that is available for the attacker.

96
00:07:45,070 --> 00:07:50,820
Based on this the main attack models
are classified four categories.

97
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:55,178
It is always assumed that the encryption
algorithm is known by the attacker.

98
00:07:55,178 --> 00:07:59,220
In a ciphertext-only attack,

99
00:07:59,220 --> 00:08:02,978
the attacker has access only
to the encrypted content.

100
00:08:02,978 --> 00:08:07,880
In a known-plaintext attack,
the attacker has access to

101
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:11,350
some plain text ciphertext pairs
which correspond to each other.

102
00:08:12,660 --> 00:08:18,760
In a chosen plaintext attack, the attacker
has access to the encryption process and

103
00:08:18,760 --> 00:08:23,770
is able to generate the corresponding
cipher text for a chosen plaintext.

104
00:08:25,170 --> 00:08:26,970
In a chosen ciphertext attack,

105
00:08:26,970 --> 00:08:30,680
the attacker has access to
the decryption process and

106
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:35,830
is able to generate the corresponding
plaintext for a chosen cipher text.

107
00:08:35,830 --> 00:08:37,702
In all of these attack models,

108
00:08:37,702 --> 00:08:40,582
the ultimate goal is to
find out the secret key.

109
00:08:43,093 --> 00:08:46,248
In addition to the mentioned
attack models,

110
00:08:46,248 --> 00:08:51,147
if there is no such information available,
the attacker has to try all

111
00:08:51,147 --> 00:08:55,560
possible combinations of keys
until the correct one is found.

112
00:08:57,060 --> 00:09:02,130
This kind of attack is known as
an Exhaustive Key Search attack or

113
00:09:02,130 --> 00:09:03,240
a Brute force attack.

114
00:09:04,820 --> 00:09:09,322
The Cipher System can not be considered
perfect if the exhaustive search is

115
00:09:09,322 --> 00:09:11,046
the only way to find the key.

116
00:09:13,883 --> 00:09:17,501
When designing cryptographic algorithms,
the time that

117
00:09:17,501 --> 00:09:22,020
a message needs to be in the encrypted
form should be taken into account.

118
00:09:23,490 --> 00:09:26,390
This period is called a Cover Period.

119
00:09:26,390 --> 00:09:30,790
For example, in a banks transaction
a message needs to be in

120
00:09:30,790 --> 00:09:34,919
the encrypted form for a few seconds
until it reaches the receiver side.

121
00:09:36,150 --> 00:09:41,240
While in a database, a file needs
to be kept in a encrypted form for

122
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:42,590
a longer period of time.

123
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:49,210
The design of a cyber system should
always ensure that any type of attack to

124
00:09:49,210 --> 00:09:55,030
successfully find the key, would take
longer time Than the given cover period.

